    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>SOLOMONS &#38; CHAPMAN&#44;<lb/>
            Agts.&#44; Lawrence&#39;s &#34;Pure Linen&#34; Papers&#44; &#38;c.&#44;<lb/>
            SUCCESSORS TO PHILIP &#38; SOLOMONS&#44;<lb/>
            METROPOLITAN BOOKSTORE.<lb/></p>
            <p>Washington&#44; Oct. 30 1877.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. and dear friend.<lb/></p>
            <p>Your<lb/> valued favor of the 28th<lb/> and postmarked the 29th<lb/> conveying the kind in&#45;<lb/>vitation of yourself and<lb/> family to allow Ida<lb/> to accept your gen&#45;<lb/>erous hospitality&#44; is<lb/> just received&#44; and<lb/> permit me&#44; dear sir&#44;<lb/> to express my appre&#45;<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>ciation of your great<lb/> kindness and to say<lb/> that although I named<lb/> to Ida in mine of<lb/> yesterday&#44; that I<lb/> thought she had<lb/> better proceed to<lb/> N. York&#44; in accor&#45;<lb/>dance with her orig&#45;<lb/>inal programmes<lb/> this week&#44; your<lb/> personal appeal to me&#44;<lb/> couched in such<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>warm terms by quite over&#45;powered<lb/> &#91;&#63;&#93; and I submit all else<lb/> being agreeable&#8212;and thank<lb/> you sincerely for your po&#45;<lb/>liteness.<lb/></p>
            <p>Very Truly Yours<lb/>
            A. S. Solomons<lb/>
            Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
            Philadelphia<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
